\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=IB=\frac{\mbox{adj}(A)}{\det(A)}AB=\frac{\mbox{adj}(A)}{\det(A)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\,\mbox{adj}(A)=\mbox{adj}(A)A$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\,\mbox{adj}(A)=\det(A)I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{adj}(A^{T})A^{T}=\det(A^{T})I=\det(A)I$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $A\,\mbox{adj}(A^{T})^{T}=\det(A)I$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So its enough to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{adj}(A^{T})^{T}=\mbox{adj}(A)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\delta^{j}\mbox{adj}(A^{T})^{T}\delta_{k} & = & \delta^{k}\mbox{adj}(A^{T})\delta_{j}\\
 & = & \left(-1\right)^{k+j}\det(A_{jk}^{T})\\
 & = & \left(-1\right)^{k+j}\det(A_{kj})\\
 & = & \delta^{j}\mbox{adj}(A)\delta_{k}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $BA=AB=I$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exterior product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the exterior product 
\begin_inset Formula $[a_{1},\ldots,a_{n-1}]$
\end_inset

 to be a vector that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $[a_{1},\ldots,a_{n-1}]\cdot b=\det(a_{1},\ldots,a_{n-1},b)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\ldots,a_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 are dependent, than their exterior product is the 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall k\in1..n-1\quad[a_{1},\ldots,a_{n-1}]a_{k}=\det(a_{1},\dots,a_{n-1},a_{k})=0$
\end_inset

 and the exterior product is a vector in the orthogonal complement to the
 sub-space of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 that is spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\ldots,a_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's size is
\begin_inset Formula $\det(a_{1},\ldots,a_{n-1},\hat{n}),$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

 is the normal to the sub-space.
 this is the area of the parallelepiped created by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\ldots,a_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Volume identities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Vol}(a,b,c)=\left(a\times b\right)\cdot c=\varepsilon_{ijk}a_{i}b_{j}c_{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\times b=\delta_{i}\left(\varepsilon_{ijk}a_{j}b_{k}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $a\times\left(b\times c\right)=\left(a\cdot c\right)b-\left(a\cdot b\right)c$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a\times\left(b\times c\right) & = & \delta_{i}\varepsilon_{ijk}a_{j}(b\times c)_{k}\\
 & = & \delta_{i}\varepsilon_{ijk}a_{j}\varepsilon_{krs}b_{r}c_{s}\\
 & = & \delta_{i}\varepsilon_{kij}\varepsilon_{krs}a_{j}b_{r}c_{s}\\
 & = & \delta_{i}\left(\delta_{i}^{r}\delta_{j}^{s}-\delta_{i}^{s}\delta_{j}^{r}\right)a_{j}b_{r}c_{s}\\
 & = & \delta_{i}\left(a_{j}b_{i}c_{j}-a_{j}b_{j}c_{i}\right)\\
 & = & \delta_{i}\left(\left(a\cdot c\right)b_{i}-\left(a\cdot b\right)c_{i}\right)\\
 & = & \left(a\cdot c\right)b-\left(a\cdot b\right)c
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $a\times\left(b\times a\right)=\left(a\times b\right)\times a=\left\Vert a\right\Vert ^{2}P_{a}^{\perp}(b)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using anti-symmetry,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a\times\left(b\times a\right) & = & -a\times\left(a\times b\right)=\left(a\times b\right)\times a
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\left(a\times b\right)\times a\right)\cdot a=\det(a\times b,a,a)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\times b\right)\times a$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The size of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\times b\right)\times a$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert a\right\Vert \left\Vert b\times a\right\Vert \sin90^{\circ}=\left\Vert a\right\Vert \left\Vert b\times a\right\Vert =\left\Vert a\right\Vert ^{2}\left\Vert b\right\Vert \sin(a,b)=\left\Vert a\right\Vert ^{2}\left\Vert P_{a}^{\perp}(b)\right\Vert $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cramer's rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is invertible, and we want to find 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's look at the determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(a_{1},\dots,a_{k-1},b,a_{k+1},\ldots,a_{n})$
\end_inset

 where we replace the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{k}^{\text{th}}$
\end_inset

 column with vector 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\det(a_{1},\dots,b,\ldots,a_{n}) & = & \det(a_{1},\dots,Ax,\ldots,a_{n})\\
 & = & \det(a_{1},\dots,a_{k}x_{k},\ldots,a_{n})\\
 & = & x_{k}\det(A)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{k}=\frac{\det(a_{1},\dots,a_{k-1},b,a_{k+1},\ldots,a_{n})}{\det(A)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Inverse of a matrix as an exterior product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{adj}(A)A=\det\left(A\right)I$
\end_inset

, therefore, every row in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{adj}(A)$
\end_inset

 is satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\delta^{j}\mbox{adj}(A)\right)a_{i}=\delta_{ij}\det(A)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\delta^{j}\mbox{adj}(A)\right)=\left(-1\right)^{n-j}[a_{1},\ldots,\check{a_{j}},\ldots,a_{n}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And we can express the inverse using the exterior product:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta^{j}A^{-1}=\frac{\left(-1\right)^{n-j}[a_{1},\ldots,\check{a_{j}},\ldots,a_{n}]}{\det A}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Vol}(a_{1},\ldots,a_{r})=\sqrt{\det A^{T}A}\qquad\left(a_{k}\in R^{n}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the QR decomposition, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=QR$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A^{T}A & = & R^{T}Q^{T}QR\\
 & = & R^{T}R\\
 & = & \left(\mbox{diag}(R)\right)^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By Gram-Schmidt, we know that the entries on the diagonal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, are the lengths of the parallelepiped heights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Divergence theorem: 
\begin_inset Formula $\oiint_{\partial V}A\cdot d\mathbf{s}=\iiint_{V}\left(\nabla\cdot A\right)dV$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will first prove it on small rectangular cuboids that have edges which
 are parallel to the axes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine such a cuboid that has it's center at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

, and edges lengths of 
\begin_inset Formula $dx,dy,dz$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
let's compute the flux flowing via the faces that are parallel to the 
\begin_inset Formula $YZ$
\end_inset

 plane.
 The normals are facing outwards, parallel to the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis, and in opposite directions.
 the size of each face is 
\begin_inset Formula $dy\,dz$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 on these two faces is approx 
\begin_inset Formula $A(x+\frac{dx}{2},y,z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A(x-\frac{dx}{2},y,z)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the flux via these two faces is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A(x+\frac{dx}{2},y,z)\begin{pmatrix}1\\
0\\
0
\end{pmatrix}dydz-A(x-\frac{dx}{2},y,z)\begin{pmatrix}1\\
0\\
0
\end{pmatrix}dydz & = & \frac{A_{1}(x+\frac{dx}{2},y,z)-A_{1}(x-\frac{dx}{2},y,z)}{dx}dxdydz\\
 & = & \frac{\partial A_{1}(x,y,z)}{\partial x}dxdydz
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the same reasoning, we see that for all the faces, the total flux
 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot Adxdydz=\nabla\cdot AdV$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For more complex volumes, we use lot's of tiny cuboids.
 The faces of neighboring cuboids cancel each other, therefore only the
 flux via the shell's surface is contributing.
\end_layout

